<font color="#FF0000">HOW TO PREVENT ANOTHER 'NAM</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  2  8:38:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This thread comes from several other threads at this site, but primarily from Docdel's question in Vietnam Protest.  AFter reading a litany of sins committed by the American government, presented by Jeffery Winkler, doc wrote, more or less, &quot;OK, so WE&quot;RE the government, what should we do?&quot;  It seems to me to be the most important question one could ask.<br><br>
If I might over-simplify the answers that have appeared so far in Vietnam Protest, we should:<br>
1. as individuals, not serve in a war sponsored by the American government because it's probably immoral.<br>
2. not elect bad people, like Johnson, Nixon, Bush...<br>
3.  not crawfish out of a war because then we're abandoning our allies.<br>
Number one is essentially a pacifist position, which I can respect, because - let's face it - all war is immoral.  However, sometimes war is necessary.  Self-preservation strikes me as one obvious reason why war is sometimes necessary.<br>
2.  First of all, I don't think Johnson, Nixon... were bad people (OK, maybe Nixon was a bad guy..).  They were human beings coming into situations with a certain set of experiences which pre-disposed them to act in certain ways.  We are never going to elect a leader who is incapable of leading us into a mistaken war.<br>
3.  I don't think this is the answer either, because sometimes, as in Vietnam, the initial mistake of getting involved in the first place is only further compounded by staying &quot;as long as necessary&quot;.<br>
I don't have an &quot;answer&quot; myself to this question, though I think about it alot.  However, it does seem to me that we have to be willing to let our leaders make and acknowledge mistakes.  Look what happened to McNamara when he finally admitted that Vietnam was a mistake (one can quibble that he didn't really admit HE made a mistake).  He got dumped on big time.  This doesn't exactly encourage honesty and intestinal fortitude in our elected officials.  There are other examples of politicians with the guts to admit they made a mistake, but rather than being accepted, they are viewed as weak or stupid.  We need to change that.<br><br>
Other ideas?
